events.description: The release of annual and monthly inflation data for Austria in January 2026 showing a significant decline.

facts.fact_text: Austria's annual inflation rate fell to 2% in January 2026 from 3.8% in December 2025.

evidences.evidence_text: The annual inflation rate in Austria eased to 2% in January 2026 from 3.8% in the previous month.

facts.fact_text: Energy prices in Austria dropped by 4.9% in January 2026.

evidences.evidence_text: mainly driven by a 4.9% drop in energy prices

facts.fact_text: Consumer prices in Austria decreased by 0.7% on a monthly basis in January.

evidences.evidence_text: On a monthly basis, consumer prices fell by 0.7% in January

facts.fact_text: Inflation for services slowed to 3.8% and food, tobacco, and alcohol slowed to 2.7%.

evidences.evidence_text: while inflation for services and for food, tobacco and alcohol slowed to 3.8% and 2.7%, respectively.

claims.claim_text: Inflation in Austria will return to levels seen in the second half of 2024 following high rates in 2025.
claims.author: Manuela Lenk

evidences.evidence_text: This means that, following the high inflation rates of 2025, inflation in Austria will fall back to the levels seen in the second half of 2024.

claims.claim_text: Energy and industrial goods had a dampening effect on the overall inflation rate.
claims.author: Manuela Lenk

evidences.evidence_text: Electricity, gas, heating oil, fuel and industrial goods had a dampening effect

evidence.evidence_text: mainly driven by a 4.9% drop in energy prices after the base effects of the electricity price cap faded, energy taxes were cut, and renewable energy subsidies were reduced.

energy taxes were cut, and renewable energy subsidies were reduced.
